        <h3>📘 Chapter 3: Coordinate Geometry</h3>
        <p>Coordinate Geometry combines algebra and geometry using the <b>Cartesian coordinate system</b>.</p>

        <h4>1. Cartesian System</h4>
        <p>Plane divided into 4 quadrants by X-axis & Y-axis. Origin (0,0).</p>

        <h4>2. Coordinates of a Point</h4>
        <p>(x,y) where x = abscissa, y = ordinate.</p>

        <h4>3. Quadrants</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>I Quadrant (+,+)</li>
          <li>II Quadrant (–,+)</li>
          <li>III Quadrant (–,–)</li>
          <li>IV Quadrant (+,–)</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>4. Distance Between Points (Preview)</h4>
        <p>AB = √((x₂ – x₁)² + (y₂ – y₁)²)</p>

        <h4>📌 Summary</h4>
        <p>Coordinate Geometry gives a way to represent points and figures on a plane using ordered pairs.</p>
      </div>
